---
import FeaturePageLayout from "../../layouts/FeaturePageLayout.astro";
import DownloadButton from "../../components/button/DownloadButton";
import DownloadMuseHubButton from "../../components/button/DownloadMuseHubButton";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import AudacityMockUp from "../../assets/img/HeroBannerImage.webp";
import Shortcut from "../../components/Shortcut.astro";
---

<FeaturePageLayout
  title="Free Audio Speed Changer – Slow Down or Speed Up Audio | Audacity"
  description="Change audio tempo without affecting pitch. Slow down music to practice, speed up podcasts, or fit audio to exact length. Free tempo changer for Windows, Mac & Linux."
  canonical="https://www.audacityteam.org/features/speed-changer/"
>
  <Fragment slot="hero">
    <section id="main" class="bg-gradient-to-r from-indigo-900 to-blue-700">
      <div class="mx-auto px-4 md:px-8 py-4 md:py-8 lg:py-12 max-w-screen-lg">
        <div
          class="flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center md:justify-between gap-8 md:gap-12"
        >
          <div class="flex flex-col text-center md:text-left md:w-1/2 gap-6">
            <h1
              class="text-xl sm:text-2xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl font-semibold text-white leading-tight"
            >
              Free Audio Speed Changer &ndash; Slow Down or Speed Up Without
              Pitch Change
            </h1>
            <p class="text-white text-lg opacity-90">
              Slow down music for practice, speed up podcasts, or fit narration
              to exact duration while preserving natural pitch.
            </p>

            <div
              class="flex flex-col w-full md:w-fit gap-4 items-center md:items-start pb-2"
            >
              <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
              <noscript>
                <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
              </noscript>
              <DownloadButton client:load />
              <noscript>
                <DownloadButton client:load />
              </noscript>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="hidden md:block md:w-1/2">
            <div class="relative">
              <Image
                src={AudacityMockUp}
                alt="A laptop showing the Audacity application"
                width={668}
                quality={80}
                loading="eager"
                class="w-full h-auto"
              />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <div class="not-prose my-8 rounded-lg border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 p-6">
    <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900">
      Change tempo in 4 steps:
    </h3>
    <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-blue-800">
      <li>Select the audio you want to speed up or slow down</li>
      <li>
        Go to <strong>Effect &rarr; Pitch and Tempo &rarr; Change Tempo</strong>
      </li>
      <li>Set target speed by percent, BPM, or final length</li>
      <li>Click <strong>Apply</strong></li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <h2>What Is Tempo Change?</h2>
  <p>
    Tempo change modifies playback speed while keeping pitch constant. That
    means voices and instruments remain in the same key, just faster or slower.
    It is ideal for practice, transcription, and timing adjustments where
    pitch-shifting would sound unnatural.
  </p>

  <div
    class="not-prose my-6 rounded-lg border border-indigo-200 bg-indigo-50 p-6"
  >
    <p class="text-indigo-800">
      Tempo change is perfect when you need <strong
        >speed changes without chipmunk or deepened voices</strong
      >. Slow a solo down to learn it note by note, or speed speech up to save
      listening time.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>How to Change Tempo in Audacity</h2>
  <h3>Step 1: Select Your Audio</h3>
  <p>
    Import your file and select the target region. For full-track edits, press <Shortcut
      keys="Ctrl+A"
    />.
  </p>

  <h3>Step 2: Open Change Tempo</h3>
  <p>
    Open <strong>Effect &gt; Pitch and Tempo &gt; Change Tempo</strong>. This
    effect is designed specifically for speed changes that preserve pitch.
  </p>

  <h3>Step 3: Set Target Speed</h3>
  <p>
    Choose the control mode you prefer: percent change, BPM values, or exact
    output length. Audacity automatically links these fields, so changing one
    updates the others.
  </p>

  <h3>Step 4: Apply</h3>
  <p>
    Preview the result, then click <strong>Apply</strong>. For long projects,
    process in sections if you want to compare different settings quickly.
  </p>

  <h2>Change Tempo Settings Explained</h2>
  <h3>Percent Change</h3>
  <p>
    Adjust speed as a percentage. <strong>-50%</strong> means half speed (double duration),
    while <strong>+100%</strong>
    means double speed (half duration).
  </p>

  <h3>Beats Per Minute (BPM)</h3>
  <p>
    Enter original and target BPM to match tracks musically. Audacity computes
    the required tempo shift automatically. This is useful for remixing and beat
    alignment.
  </p>

  <h3>Length (Seconds)</h3>
  <p>
    Set the exact output duration when fitting narration, ads, or cues to strict
    timing windows. Enter the desired "to" length and let Audacity solve the
    tempo change.
  </p>

  <h3>Use High Quality Stretching</h3>
  <p>
    Enable this for cleaner transients, especially on drums, piano, and
    rhythm-heavy material. It takes longer but improves quality for harder
    sources.
  </p>

  <div
    class="not-prose my-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50"
  >
    <table class="w-full text-sm text-left">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-gray-100">
          <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-gray-900">Percent Change</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-gray-900">Speed</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-gray-900">New Length</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200 text-gray-700">
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">-50%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">0.5x</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">2x longer</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">-25%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">0.75x</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">1.33x longer</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">0%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">1x</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Same length</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">+50%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">1.5x</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">0.67x shorter</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">+100%</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">2x</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">0.5x shorter</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>Common Use Cases</h2>
  <div
    class="not-prose my-6 rounded-lg border border-green-200 bg-green-50 p-6"
  >
    <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-green-900">
      Where speed changing helps most:
    </h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
      <li>
        <strong>Practice music</strong> &ndash; Slow down technical passages and solos.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Speech transcription</strong> &ndash; Reduce speed to catch every
        word.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Podcast listening</strong> &ndash; Speed up content to 1.5x or 2x.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Time fitting</strong> &ndash; Fit narration to ad slots and scene
        timing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>BPM matching</strong> &ndash; Align tracks for DJ and editing workflows.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Language learning</strong> &ndash; Slow native speech while preserving
        tone.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Tips for Best Results</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Keep changes moderate (within ±50%) for the most natural result.</li>
    <li>Enable high-quality stretching for percussion-rich material.</li>
    <li>
      For extreme slowdowns, use Paulstretch instead of standard tempo change.
    </li>
    <li>Always preview before applying to check for artifacts.</li>
    <li>
      For long audio, test on a short section first and then apply globally.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Does Change Tempo affect pitch?</strong><br />No. Change Tempo is
    specifically designed to preserve pitch while changing speed.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong
      >What is the difference between Change Tempo and Change Speed?</strong
    ><br />Change Tempo keeps pitch unchanged. Change Speed changes both tempo
    and pitch together.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>How do I slow a song to half speed?</strong><br />Set Percent Change
    to -50%.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Can I speed a podcast to 1.5x?</strong><br />Yes. Set Percent Change
    to +50%.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>How can I hit an exact final duration?</strong><br />Use the Length
    fields and enter the target "to" value.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why does it sound distorted after large changes?</strong><br />Very
    large shifts can introduce artifacts. Use high-quality stretching and
    smaller adjustments where possible.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Is there a hard maximum tempo change?</strong><br />You can push
    large values, but quality usually degrades as changes become extreme.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Can I preview speeds during playback?</strong><br />Yes, the
    playback speed control lets you audition timing without permanently
    processing audio.
  </p>

  <h2>Download Audacity Free</h2>
  <p>
    Ready to speed up or slow down audio with precision? Download Audacity for
    free on Windows, macOS, and Linux.
  </p>
  <div
    class="not-prose mt-8 flex flex-col w-full md:w-fit gap-4 items-center sm:items-start text-left"
  >
    <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
    <noscript>
      <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
    </noscript>
    <DownloadButton client:load />
    <noscript>
      <DownloadButton client:load />
    </noscript>
  </div>
</FeaturePageLayout>
